    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1911-12-23T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1911-12-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="202"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d202">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 738.3915/91.</note>
                <head>[Untitled]</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Port au Prince</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1911-12-23">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 23, 1911</hi>.</date>
                    </dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 993.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to state that upon the receipt
                    of the Department’s December 21, 6 p.m., I immediately called upon Secretary
                    Legér and took up the matter with him.</p>
                <p>It happened that we had already discussed, earlier in the day, the
                    Haitian-Dominican boundary question, and Mr. Legér told me that he had had some
                    correspondence with the Dominican minister relative thereto.</p>
                <p>Mr. Léger stated that it is the keen desire of the Haitian Government to have
                    this matter settled at the earliest possible moment, and <pb facs="0249" n="167"
                        xml:id="pg_167"/> that if the powers already given their representative at
                    Washington are not sufficient, the Haitian Government is willing and anxious to
                    add to them at the suggestion of the Department of State.</p>
                <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">H. W. Furniss.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
